{"key":"post-11725231","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11725231</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;RedDevil420 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Nah, if you mist up into the air, a nice light mist sprinkles on the mushrooms and adds a humididy cloud.&amp;nbsp; The idea is that you want the caps to return to being slightly dry after you fan them because if it is really soaked it can contam easier.&amp;nbsp; Also, I've had defects with overwatering directly.&amp;nbsp; Soaking them is not good.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You should have enough water in the casing and substrate for the flush, else dunk it.&amp;nbsp; Misting is just to add a bit of humidity to the surface.&amp;nbsp; You shouldnt need to soak it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This is absolutely incorrect, and based on ten year old advice that for some reason keeps getting repeated, fucking up people's projects.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Misting is NOT to provide humidity.&amp;nbsp; That is the job of the perlite.&amp;nbsp; Misting is to replace the moisture that evaporates from the substrate due to giving proper fresh air exchange.&amp;nbsp; Even at 99% humidity, your cakes will dry out if they're getting the proper fresh air.&amp;nbsp; In addition, as fruits form, they draw lots of water from the substrate, and will totally dry out a small cake before the flush is finished if you don't replace that water by misting.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11725478</next>\n<prev>11724339</prev>\n<first>11723689</first>\n<last>11819557</last>\n<when>1261932365</when>\n<utime>12/27/09 06:46 PM</utime>\n</post>"}